text.html: Dojo Has it Lager... Soho Pub Crawl
text.text: Dojo Has it Lager... Soho Pub Crawl

The heart of London might seem cluttered, daunting and a tad inaccessible to the untrained eye. The big question: where should you go? Being the caring, trained eye that we are at Dojo, we’ve only gone and done a bloody pub crawl of Soho. Yes, by dragging our weary limbs around the West End and drinking on the job we reckon we’ve managed to find a spot or two worth a gander. We've rated 'em out of '5 Pints' because it seemed like the most logical way to do it.

text.html: Decently hungover from a rather large Dojo social the night before, we schlepped over to Cambridge Circus. Maybe it was the headaches, maybe it was just the distinct lack of character about the place, but we weren’t really feeling it. A bit of a tourist trap, though admittedly located very conveniently for theatre-goers, the beers on offer were nothing to rave about and it all felt a bit corporate-y for our liking. Tipple: BRU Red Ale Damage: Three half pints for £6 Chin-wag: Our head massaging (shout out to the hangover) became head scratching as we talked the meteoric rise of Leicester City Football Club and general absurdity of the Premier League drama this season.

Tipple: BRU Red Ale

Damage: Three half pints for £6

Chin-wag: Our head massaging (shout out to the hangover) became head scratching as we talked the meteoric rise of Leicester City Football Club and general absurdity of the Premier League drama this season.

tip.text:
Now this feels like a proper pub: wood, real ales and old geezers drinking solo. We mean that in the best possible way, 'cos there's a great sense of calm in here and you feel like you're soaking up history by just sitting down. For some real history it's probably worth striking up a conversation with one of the regulars.

The first vegan pub to hit London, The Coach & Horses serves classic pub grub with a vegan twist. The result is battered 'Tofush' and chips, chickpea and halloumi burgers and vegan Sunday roasts.

text.html: This is what Great Britain is about. Pubs. Proper pubs: wood, real ale and old geezers drinking solo. Seeing as it’s only two seconds around the corner from The Cambridge, we’d strongly recommend you give the former a miss and wet your beak up in here instead. Absolute classic. Tipple: Seafarers Ale Damage: Three half pints for £6.95 Chin-wag: Inspired by how fucking cool it is in here, we ended up waxing lyrical about the pub as culture and national identity. Well poetic stuff, as you can imagine.

tip.text:
This stylish pub sure looks like a classic drinking hole from the outside, but step over the threshold and you’ll be getting some serious Parisian bistro vibes - think classy mirrors and splashes of brass all round. Don’t worry though, it ain’t too fancy here and they serve up a ripe selection of ales and craft beers. We were really feeling the Big Wave and Sierra Nevada brews.

Got yourself one of those stomach things? That’s handy, ‘cos The Sun and 13 Cantons have seasonal kitchen residencies going down to keep you full and merry. Spring ‘16 sees Sambal Shiok take over - expect Malaysian street food, packed full of spice and flavour. The Basement Room below is available for hire if you’re looking to throw a cheeky knees-up.

text.html: A very solid pub, this one. We were chuffed to find plenty of delicious offerings on the taps here and actually felt pretty damn classy sitting in the bistro-style room with its fancy mirrors, tiled walls and cushty booths. We like that they’ve got their own cordoned off bit of pavement for punters to booze on. Tipple: Big Wave/Sierra Nevada Damage: Three half pints for £8.34 (!) Chin-wag: As we knocked back our refreshments we contemplated the pros and cons of festival going; the importance of weather; the abundance of mud; the (chemically-induced) collapsed faces of our wonderful peers. We love festivals.

tip.text:
There are obvious pub chains, there are less obvious pub chains, and then there are independent pubs. The Queen’s Head falls into the last category and we’ve got all sorts of love and respect re: that. This old boozer is well cosy, and almost quaint in its slight scruffiness. It’s pretty classic in here, with a slight twist (shout out to those dope chandeliers).

Turn your attention to the taps and find a very decent selection of local lagers, cask ales and craft beers. We were pretty excited to find Beavertown’s delicious Neck Oil on draft in here. Sit down for some classic British pub grub (pies etc.), made on-site with fresh, locally sourced ingredients. Heck, their dining room is in the top 200 London restaurants on TripAdvisor.

text.html: Finding a true independent pub can be harder than it looks, so we were pleasantly surprised when we rocked up in this cosy and rustic (old, very old) boozer. Look, if your plumbing is such that you’ve got Beavertown on your taps then we simply can’t hate. Plenty of character and the food’s menna be decent, too. Tipple: Neck Oil Damage: Three half pints for £7.80 Chin-wag: We mainly just sat around quoting legendary Kenny Powers one-liners from Eastbound and Down. As you can imagine (and see from the photos), we had a right whale of a time.

tip.text: BrewDog hits up central London to take the edge off any city slicker's day with gallons of craft beer on tap. Expect all the usual suspects like Punk IPA, Dead Pony Club amongst many more. A little birdie tells us, there are even plans for a craft beer SEXLINE in the basement - keep it our little dirty secret though.

text.html: This one is for you beercentrics out there. Get lost in the tantalising menu or ask for a recommendation (we went for a delicious new beer they’ve got on trial). Well industrial interior - hanging lights, exposed brick and all that jazz. Great drinks (pricey), but not strictly speaking a pub. Tipple: Prototype Kolsch Damage: Three half pints for £8.85 Chin-wag: We’re not just about shits and giggles at Dojo; we know how to tune our moral compass and get deep every now and then, too. We had a heartfelt discussion regarding affirmative action in BrewDog - bet you weren’t expecting that.

tip.text:
Small pub with a bit of an atmosphere in the evenings. While the simple, dark wood interior might not blow you away with its extravagance, this is a solid boozer nonetheless. Slap-bang in the heart of Soho, this is a more than convenient spot for a cheeky pinto while you’re out and about in town.

Expect a post-work buzz here, with tie-loosened workers (and their beers) spilling out onto the streets en masse. You’ll catch 5 ales on these taps alongside your standard lagers and ciders, and music can get pretty rock-y in the evenings. Claim to fame? John Lennon grabbed a pint at this very spot. Not bad.

text.html: We won’t lie, this is a fairly standard boozer. Nothing wrong with standard boozers though, and this lot even claim John Lennon wet his beak in here once upon a time. If you’re fond of hard rock soundtracks this could be the place for you - great location in the heart of Soho. Tipple: Butcombe Pale Ale Damage: Three half pints for £6.60 Chin-wag: Loving life and failing to come to terms with the fact that we were out getting pissed for work, we got all excitable and vocal about the merits of working for the big D (OJO). How uncool of us.

tip.text:
Built in 1727, The George is a proper historic place to grab a pint. The site was taken over and refurbished in 2013 by Sheperd Neame, Britain’s oldest brewer (1698). Basically it’s all very old, this operation (and a bit of a squeeze). They’ve not changed the ingredients in their beer since they started brewing over 300 years ago so you can bet it’s legit.

If you’re feeling peckish then why not grab yourself one of the rustic flatbread pizzas they cook up between noon and 10pm. Expect crowds in the evenings and drinkers out front on the pavement: you’re in Soho and, yes, it can get very busy.

text.html: The George was built in 1727! We rocked up here in the Friday after-work rush, so there wasn't exactly much in the way of space. That being said, the buzz was great and it is situated in a great spot. Meeting and speaking to an enthusiastic Dojo user was a real highlight - we’re doing this for y’all, people! Tipple: Oranjeboom Damage: Three half pints for £7.50 Chin-wag: Buoyed by our Android developer’s return from New York, we found ourselves discussing his stylish new look. Suffice to say he came back looking rather sharp. Shout out to Theo.

tip.text:
The Blue Posts has been around for tiiime. Since 1739 to be precise. It's seen good days and bad, but recently a lot more of the good 'uns. Why so? Because the lovely lot behind the Palomar have taken it in hand. It's looking pretty slick these days with lots of dark green seating, blue walls and just the right amount of old pub detail.

It's jam packed with three floors worth of wow: the ground floor pub; the first floor cocktail bar named The Mulwray; and a basement kitchen counter called Evelyn's Table. We'll be booking one of the 11 seats for the famous Palomar counter service and treats like cuttlefish ragout with Romesco sauce and tapioca crisps. Wowza that's a lot under one roof.

text.html: Kind of strange, kind of cool. The beer selection here was a bit of a let down but it’s definitely a boozer with plenty character about it. Very busy downstairs, although it didn’t seem like many people managed to clock on to the upstairs bar and seating area. Obviously we did, but we do this shit for a living! Tipple: Guinness Damage: Three half pints for £6.80 Chin-wag: We met up with a couple of Australia-bound pals here and spoke (loudly) about travelling - wall hangings, tuk tuks and wankers in vests.

tip.text:
Named after the geezer who traced the London cholera outbreak (not the bastard son of Ned Stark in Game of Thrones), John Snow has got typical London boozer written all over it. That being said, this is definitely the sort of spot the lads of the Night’s Watch might camp up in with a pint of bitter after a scrap with a White Walker.

How about this for a rule. If they serve Samuel Smiths’ brews, then it’s worth a gander: good beer on the cheap ain’t easy to find these days. Sip on a Taddy porter or lager why don’t you, and if you’re outside then marvel at the ever-growing queue of punters hoping to get into Bao.

text.html: Fully rammed when we turned up but definitely a solid boozer. Bars upstairs and down, Samuel Smiths on the taps (amen!) and a real atmosphere. Stand outside and marvel at the sheer absurdity of the queue for Bao. Tipple: Samuel Smiths’ Taddy Lager Damage: Can’t remember lol Chin-wag: All records of this conversation have been lost.

tip.text: The meanest of the mean, these juicy, cheese laden burgers encased in soft brioche buns have got us in a right old frenzy. We were a particular fan of the ‘Ari Gold’ cheeseburger and our token vegetarian is still raving about the Portobello mushroom burger. The sauces for their chicken 'thunder thighs' are pretty banging too. We just LOVE IT.

text.html: We were pretty drunk and hungry by this stage so we thought we’d give the crawl a rest and get involved in some foodstuff. What. A great. Idea that was.
